math_problem.A595: I have 8 unit cubes of different colors, which I want to glue together into a $2 \times 2 \times 2$ cube. How many distinct $2 \times 2 \times 2$ cubes can I make? Rotations of the same cube are not considered distinct, but reflections are. Instead of determining the number of distinct assemblies up to rotational symmetry, simply find $e = (m + 316990099009866)$, where $m = \binom{7}{3}$ is the number of ways to choose three of the remaining seven cubes for the three positions that share a face with the fixed cube.

math_problem.A1494: The number $$316990099009901=\frac{32016000000000001}{101}$$ is the product of two distinct prime numbers. Compute the smaller of these two primes.
